To make a class `Com` async, you can use the `async` keyword before the class keyword, and then define an `async` method for each of the methods you want to make asynchronous. For example:
```
class Com {
  isConnected() {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      setTimeout(() => {
        resolve(true);
      }, 1000);
    });
  }

  connect() {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      setTimeout(() => {
        resolve("Connected");
      }, 1000);
    });
  }

  do() {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      setTimeout(() => {
        resolve("Done");
      }, 1000);
    });
  }
}
```
In this example, the `isConnected`, `connect`, and `do` methods are all declared as `async` and return a `Promise` that resolves after a 1 second delay. This allows the methods to be used asynchronously and will not block the execution of the program.

You can then use the `await` keyword to wait for the promise to resolve before continuing with the rest of the program. For example:
```
const com = new Com();

com.isConnected().then(() => {
  console.log("Is connected");
});

com.connect().then(() => {
  console.log("Connected");
});

com.do().then(() => {
  console.log("Done");
});
```
In this example, the `isConnected`, `connect`, and `do` methods are called asynchronously using the `await` keyword. The program will continue executing and print "Is connected" and "Connected" before waiting for the promises to resolve and printing "Done".

